 beliefs about the masculine foundations of citizenship. Piecing together material from national and regional archives, popular journalism, and oral histories, Olcott examines how women inhabited the conventionally manly role of citizen by weaving together its "idian and formal traditions, drawing strategies from local political struggles and competing gender ideologies.Olcott demonstrates an extraordinary grasp of the complexity of postrevolutionary Mexican politics, exploring the goals and outcomes of women's organizing in Mexico City and the port city of Acapulco as well as in three rural locations: the southeastern state of Yucatán, the central state of Michoacán, and the northern region of the Comarca Lagunera. Combining the strengths of national and regional approaches, this comparative perspective sets in relief the specificities of citizenship as a lived experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFeminismzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical participationzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen political activistszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen revolutionarieszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOlcott, Jocelyn H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387350zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387350.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHAL